561	\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}
562	
563	For a proper geometrically integral curve $C$ over $k$, a two-affine cover with affine intersection always exists. The bundle $S$ then feeds the Serre-finiteness chain:
564	\begin{enumerate}
565	  \item The Mayer--Vietoris LES applied to $S$ and $\mathcal O_C$ relates $H^0$ and $H^1$ of $C$, $U_1$, $U_2$, and $U_1 \cap U_2$.
566	  \item The cover hypothesis identifies the fourth corner with the whole curve.
567	  \item Affineness of the pieces collapses $H^{>0}$ on those pieces, reducing the LES to a three-term sequence.
568	  \item Finiteness of each $H^0$ piece then implies finiteness of $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$.
569	\end{enumerate}
570	Steps~1--2 are supplied by this section; Steps~3--4 are deferred to subsequent sections.
571	
572	\section{Cohomology of the whole space}
573	\label{sec:cover_totality}
574	
575	The abstract cohomology $H^n(X, \mathcal F)$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule}) lives at a different universe level from the open-flavour cohomology $H^{\prime n}(U, \mathcal F)$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}). To transport results from the Mayer--Vietoris sequence---which lives at the open-flavour level---to the whole-space carrier $H^n(X, \mathcal F)$, we need a bridge between the two. This section constructs that bridge when the open $U$ is the total space.
576	
577	\subsection{Source-object identification}
578	
579	\begin{definition}\leanok
580	[Source-object isomorphism for a terminal object]
581	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_top_sourceIso}
582	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_top_sourceIso}
